segments.text: So you had done so well in Venezuela, and that's why you think that they chose you for that job, because you would oversee this duty.
Yes.
That probably came out on my record.
In fact, the Venezuela Army had asked for me to return to Venezuela.
Really?
Yeah.
But the Army wouldn't?
No.
And I didn't feel at that time I should go back.
But it never really was seriously considered.
Now what were your first impressions when you arrived in Yugoslavia in June 1959?
Well of course I went with my family and my first impression was, on the first day, was by golly I can't use this language because I had to.
And we went in of course through Trieste, Ljubljana, and Zagreb to Belgrade.
To tell you the truth, it was very obvious you're in another country when you leave Italy.
Oh, yeah.
Very obvious.
It's just like you can go out here and look at a piece of land and look across the fence and it's obvious that's somebody else's across the fence.
The people weren't dressed as well.
The buildings were not maintained as well.
The roads were not as good.
The facilities just didn't look like that they'd been taken care of.
There wasn't much new in general in terms of structures.
It just was a little bit depressing, to tell you the truth.
What were your functions?
You said that basically you were on your own.
What did you do with your time?
Basically on your own.
Oh, we were busy.
Again, my primary function was intelligence.
How many did you have in your stay out?
I had two officers and two enlisted men and a civilian.
And were you housed in the embassy?
No, we had quarters designated by the Yugoslav Army for the U.S. Attaché, and very adequate, by the way, a big old villa on about two acres of land, probably.
Just before we left, they took much of that land away.
And your family could see it?
It was really pretty extravagant.
Oh, yes.
And that's where my family and I lived.
And we were

We had a staff of servants because, well, to get into the functions, first of all, you've got to have servants if you fulfill this function, this job, by the way, because the wife is just as committed, really, basically, as you are.
And she, by the way, looked at just as carefully, if not more so, than the officer when this selection is made to send you on attache duty.
And the reason I say she's looked at more carefully is because there's a record on me, but there's not a record on her in the files.
Secondly, after the intelligence function, and it can be put first if your ambassador wants it to be, you're an advisor to the ambassador.
You're a member of his staff.
You head his army section.
Thirdly,
you are a diplomatic representative to the Yugoslav Army.
I'm getting my countries mixed up here.
In other words, I think in my two years there, I had one formal message to deliver to the Army of Venezuela.
You mean Yugoslavia?
I mean Yugoslavia.
What was that?
You know, I don't even remember what the subject was, but I know at the time it was a ticklish subject.
thing wasn't great significance, but it was sensitive.
And so I delivered that formally from our chief of staff to their chief of staff.
The rest of the time it was all verbal, but I represented my army, their army, not only from office to office and message to message, but also socially, of course.
I was also part of the
as a member of the diplomatic community, you get into this whole diplomatic social scheme of things, and it sometimes is very, very overbearing.
So how did we do this job?
Because the United States and
Yugoslav governments were on good terms.
Tito, of course, was the dictator president.
This was in 1959 that I joined, which is about 10 years after Tito broke from the Russians.
It was about two years after our military training mission, MAG, Military Assistance Group, left.
And I had, by the way, the residual functions of that military assistance group, which didn't amount to a great deal.
And Yugoslavia had to struggle to survive that break with the Russians.
And our assistance to them was very important, the economic assistance as important as the military assistance.
What the military assistance did was give them credibility of military capability
so that the Russians didn't intervene.
And as history shows us now, they probably wish they had at the time, because the next one that cropped up was neighbor Hungary, and they took them just like that.
At the time that Yugoslavia broke from the Russian common form, it was estimated that
three-fourths of their trade was with the Russian communist bloc, and 25% with the rest of the world.
Well, when they broke, this had to be reversed.
They continued to trade some with their neighbors in the communist world, but they were basically cut off from trade with the organized communist group.
And so this was a great struggle for them, and this led, in my opinion, to the
perception later that Yugoslav communism is different.
Yugoslav communism is not so bad.

And the reason I say that I think that's what led to this misimpression here and in other parts of the world is that they had to adapt their matter of means of conducting commerce to the way we do it.
Sure.
And this even became influenced within the country, not just at their ports, in a way.
And this did make some difference in the economic picture within Yugoslavia.
And of course, once this switch was made, they became more prosperous, I would say.
Because at the time we left Yugoslavia, we could see
more consumer goods available to the Yugoslav people by far than we saw when we traveled in Bulgaria and Romania, for example.
And those are the only other two common exceptions.
Who was the ambassador, the American ambassador?
The ambassador, when I went to Yugoslavia, was Ambassador Karl Rankin, and he was
succeeded by Ambassador George Kennan, who's a very famous person.
Oh, yeah, he is.
I know George Kennan.
I admired them both a great deal.
Ambassador Rankin had come there from Formosa.
He'd been ambassador to Nationalist China for years.
He was, of course, a career diplomat.
And Kennan succeeded him just a matter of months before I left.
And we had some very interesting experiences with both of them.
What were your impressions of these two men?
My impressions were that they were real professionals and highly experienced, and we were fortunate to have them.
Ambassador Rankin was one of the calmest.
We didn't have any great uproars in our relations when we were there.
He was real steady and very much respected by the Yugoslav.
Wonderful personality, a very kind man, pleasant to be around, pleasant to be with.
I hunted with him a great deal.
He loved to hunt, particularly big game, and when he learned that I loved to hunt,
I arranged several hunts for him.
And we never had more than four in the party.
You arranged these hunts with the Yugoslav authorities?
Through the Yugoslav authorities.
And they had, by the way, some of the finest hunting in the world there for particularly the stag deer, the red deer, and the roebuck, they call them over there.
The ambassador was particularly anxious to get a bear.
They had the big brown bear.
We went bear hunting twice, but neither of us ever got a bear.
Did you ever see one?
Yes, we saw them, but we didn't see any of the boars.
Now, you could take a female if she didn't have a cub, but I never saw a female alone with what young were there, and I didn't want to shoot one that might have still had a dependent cub.
When you got up in the mountains and you were hunting, how did you get along?
How were the people?
How did they receive you up there?
Some of the most interesting
experiences I had were on these hunts with the people.
Let me say a little bit.
We're going to get to Ambassador Kennan later?
All right, fine.
As a matter of fact, there is a very stringent law in Yugoslavia and all the communist countries, and we have similar laws but not quite so stringent, about giving information to foreigners.
And the law is almost so severe in Yugoslavia to say that you don't even talk to a military attache.
It's not quite that stringent.
Well, you didn't wear your uniform out there, did you?
No, but I would never put a person in jeopardy by disguising my identity.
I would always, when I came into the company of Yugoslavs that I thought might, well, I just always identified myself.
Now, that meant that the only time that I could really have frank conversations with people, citizens, or even some of the military was when it was one-on-one.
And I never felt comfortable, as spooky as this may sound, it's true, unless we were out of doors.
In fact, when I briefed Ambassador Kennan, we went to the garden of the embassy and walked and strolled and talked.
You've got to assume that if you're in a building you normally, or the person you're talking to normally habitates, you're going to be heard.
But anyway, on these hunts, I got to meet many of the simple people.
And you can learn a lot from the simple people.
And of course, the Yugoslav people, like most people, they're very fine people.
They're very friendly to me and all Americans because nearly all of them have got a relative of some kind in America, and they think this is paradise, and they're all rich.
Oh, yeah.
And they are terribly poor by and large in Yugoslavia.
But on these hunts, I largely met a few functionaries, but my real enjoyment was some of the peasants.
And they're very solid people.

conversation with a man who was sort of my gun bearer assigned and we were alone a lot he was born and raised out there you see when you go bear hunting now you go as far as you can on wheels and you like likely you're going to have to get on a horse to finish your trip and so you're up there with the people who are pretty well isolated and they feel much more free than the citizens down in
in the cities and towns that are dealing with the communist apparatus, government apparatus.

But when this fellow described to me that he had what amounted to, I think, 10 hectares of land, Yugoslavia, and I'm digressing, but it ties in here, found that they had no chance, the communist government had no chance to communize farming the land.
And so they didn't even try.
But what they did do was pass a law of inheritance.
And by golly, ours is getting damn near as bad.
The law said that you can only inherit 10 hectares or less.
Well, all of these estates are quickly being, you know, these old land holdings are quickly being reduced to 10 hectares as inheritance occurs.
And when you get under 10 hectares, there are very few people who can make a living on it anymore.
But they can exist.

And this old peasant said that he's happier there than anybody in Yugoslavia because, he says, I've got my land, I've got my cattle, I've got my horse, I've got my dogs, I've got my family, and I've got the shumadija, the forest.
His land was on the edge of this huge forest where we went in to hunt.
And he says, when I walk in the forest, I feel a free man.
Who owned the forest?
The government.
Then he tells me, I ask him, he grows basically on the land grain and food.
And he went into detail to tell me what he earned from that grain.
And it turns out that when it
He's made all of his tax payments, some of which can be paid in kind like in grain.
He would have about a third of what he raised.
I mean, that's gross.
Then he has to pay a tax on his land.
That's his crop thing.
He has to pay a tax on his cattle.
He said, I even have to pay a tax on my dog.

And you get a very good picture of how little anybody on the land in Yugoslavia can ever realize and what they've done to gradually gain control of the vast part of the agricultural land in Yugoslavia.
Now, that ties right in.
You also get from these people when you talk to them what the effect of the police
influences and effectiveness.

And I saw that firsthand because I had a young bachelor sergeant who naturally made acquaintance with Yugoslav girls from time to time, and almost inevitably, we wouldn't hear about all of them, I'm sure, but certainly the second date he'd have with a girl,
When he took her home, the police would be there right after he left, arrest her, and grill her, and sometimes mistreat her.
Really?
Oh, yes.
You know, they're not supposed to talk back, but we'd get it back occasionally through the, I mean, I can cite two or three instances of that.
I can cite, that's firsthand, you might say firsthand knowledge, but anyway.
I saw enough to know that the police system is so efficient.

You can talk and fuss about the price of eggs and the fact that there's not a decent bus system in Belgrade or this, that, and the other, but boy, don't talk about the government because somebody hears you.
And if I can continue this digression to get back to this peasant,
I had a language school instructor, former Yugoslav.
He immigrated to this country when he was a young man.
Come to visit Belgrade, and he wrote me he was coming.
He had a brother who was married and had a child in Belgrade.
I'd never met him, of course.
And when he came, I offered to
His brother had no transportation.
Very few people had an automobile.
And this friend, former instructor, wanted to visit some of the areas around that he grew up in and knew.
And so I offered my car.
And of course, he wouldn't drive it, so I'd send my chauffeur to take him places, or take him myself.
Well, in the course of this, I had him and his wife and his brother
wife and son over for dinner.
Then they invited us out.
Each time, and one time I remember we went to the big monument there that's a famous place.
We went various places, and we'd always invite, when we picked them up, we'd invite the brother to go along.
So I guess four or five times I would return him with his brother
Each time, the brother would ask me to put him off at a different place, sometimes as much as two blocks away from his apartment.
Because it's true.
So no one would see.
It is absolutely true that out of every ten people, there's at least one listening for the system.
Mm-hmm.
and I'm sure that it works.
I know that it works.
Anyway, even as far and remote as that peasant was, he felt that influence.
I guess what he really told me was that he only feels free when he's out in that forest.
Nobody knows where he is.
Nobody sees him.
Tell me, what kind of man was George Kennan?
He was a splendid ambassador.
and a very brilliant man, I felt, and I was there just a matter of months with him.
But he came in very ambitious to really pull Yugoslavia to an accord with us, not an alliance, but a better friendship, because Yugoslavia was truly now that government.
We were friendly.
But Yugoslavia was very instrumental in the Third World Movement.
Sure.
In the non-committed movement.
And neutrals.
And neutrals.
And so Mr. Kennan felt that, in fact they were doing our policies some damage.
And I remember
first walk in the garden with Mr. Kennan.
He had each of his section chiefs brief him on the situation, what we thought, and so forth.
He wanted your ideas in addition to your information.
And while I was military, I had to tell you, I was most interested in, outside of my area, I was most interested in the political section's work and followed and worked closely with them on that.
I had gone down to the square in Belgrade to hear Tito make a speech.
to the people after he'd visited the Western Hemisphere, visited the United States.
And what he told those people angered me.
He was very critical of the United States and our policies and the way we treat Mexico and one thing or the other.
He didn't sound like a friend at all.
And I guess this was just before Kennan got there.
And that made a great impression on me.
I could understand, see?
the language he was speaking.
And that really wasn't intended for our ears, and their press doesn't necessarily report it that way.
But I remember in briefing, Mr. Ken and I brought that up.
And I said, I cannot believe that we have a chance of ever really being friends with a communist country.
And I thought this was the epitome of the evidence.
But nonetheless, he was not deterred in his objectives.
And I understand that he left Yugoslavia in great disappointment because things went from bad to worse.
And as a matter of fact, they had the Unaligned Nations Conference there in Belgrade toward the end of his tour when Yugoslavia led them to pronouncements of policy that were even
more clearly contrary to our interests.
Now would you, did you ever have an opportunity to meet Tito?
Yes, met him several times.
And what, tell me about that.
What were your impressions?
Marshal Tito was a very impressive person, of course, just his presence, but whatever you think of him,
As a communist, you've got to think of him as an accomplished man.
And you've got to give him some respect for that.
And I did.
And personally, he's pleasant.
I never spent a great deal of time with him, but I'd met him.
Well, when Mr. Kennan came to present his credentials, I accompanied Mr. Kennan to Brioni, the island of Brioni, to present his credentials to Tito.
And Tito gave him a great deal of time and, of course,
great respect because Mr. Kennedy was then well known as a very prominent thinker in terms of foreign affairs.
And we met him, met him and his wife at official functions several times, and of course observed him in ceremonies a number of times.
He's a very interesting man.

I might say I also traveled many of his battle areas of World War II when he and his partisans accomplished, you've got to admit, a great deal against the Germans, considering their limitations of resources.
So I became convinced in my own mind that probably
Most of the people in Yugoslavia admired him, respected him.
He governed very effortlessly.
He was one of those leaders that didn't have to speak many words or very loudly, it seemed.
That's the impression you get.
And all of this makes a very fine impression on any observer, Yugoslav or foreign.
The fact is that I doubt that any nation in the world has a more effective police force than he had.
And I've just alluded to it to some degree.
And so don't give all the credit of everything going so smoothly and quietly to Tito, because the consequences of not going along are very severe.

told Mr. Kennan, as a matter of fact, upon departure, when I was leaving, and again summarizing some of my views, I said, I am convinced, he had great admiration for Tito, and he felt, too, that the people respected him so well, and I told him, I think I gave this same view to him, but that I felt that if they had truly democratic elections in Yugoslavia,
and allowed an opposition party to run on the platform of a democratic form of government, almost regardless of who that might be, that Tito would get 15% of the vote.
And that the opposition would get 85.
Really?
And I would have bet anything on it.
And in other words, you didn't feel like... My reasoning was that
There's about 3% of the population who are members of the Communist Party at that time.
They've never had over five.
There's 10% that are dependent upon the Communist Party for their jobs and their future.
And then there's a small percentage that really sympathize, very small, in my opinion.
You don't think that Tito, after being that great war leader, was sort of a national hero?
He was, but if he'd offered a democratic form of government, he'd been defeated soundly, in my opinion.
What did Mr. Kennett say to that?
This is not only from talking to peasants.
I didn't finish that conversation on individuals, but I did find through those years opportunities to talk with individuals, some of them
were prominent in the prior governments.
Where did Mr. Kennan respond?
Well, he was still just there a few months.
I remember talking to a very learned and prominent Serbian individual, and he knows who I was.
It's not often you can get this opportunity.
I had great respect for the Serbs because
Well, in this year of language school, what I was really studying was Yugoslav history and its military organization, customs, terms, and so forth.
And I got a lot of that history that I'd never really studied before.
And one remarkable thing about the history of Yugoslavia, which is now a grouping of nations, former nations, you know, you've got Serbia, you've got Croatia, Slovenia, Herzegovina.
and Macedonia.
But anyway, the Serbs, when they were invaded, captured, and taken over by the Turks, were under the Turkish heel for 500 years.
They conducted 40 distinct revolutions and lost them all.
They were finally freed by the results of World War
won.
But when that 500 years of Turkish dominance was over, they still had pure Serbian blood, they still had a pure Serbian language, and they still had a pure Orthodox Serbian religion.
And I think that's remarkable.
And I had never really focused on a history of a people that was so
I thought valorous and so tenacious as theirs.
So I asked this prominent Serb in the course of this conversation, I said, when are the Serbs going to get rid of communism?
And citing my, noting their history of Turkish times, he said, I don't know that we ever can.
Much as I
and much as many of us would like to.
But he said, we have something that has never been seen before.
We have the most efficient police system that dominates us that anyone has ever known.
He said, if I went to my best friend, and he and I decided that we were obligated and determined to do something to get rid of this
communist government, we would have to go to others to gain enough strength that we could actually have the power to do something.
He said by the time he went to his next best friend and I went to my next best friend, we'd be found out.
He said, I'm convinced of that.
That's what the people dislike most.
about the Communist government, and that's one of the main reasons that I say Tito wouldn't have won his election if there was a Democratic alternative.
How'd you like being a diplomat instead of a military man?
I wasn't looking forward to that, but I enjoyed it.
And I must say that we met very interesting people from all over the world.
It was a wonderful experience, the whole thing, in all aspects.

Uh, and the Yugoslav government, being a neutralist government, insisted we all mixed instead of in some, like in some of our country, Western friendly countries, you know, the, the Reds are kind of separated from the West.
Sure.
But, uh, we enjoyed that very much and we did, uh, a great deal of entertaining ourselves, um, including not only the military diplomats, but the, the ambassadors and others and, and became, uh,
pretty good friends with some of them.
Another hunter, by the way, was the Swedish ambassador—Finnish ambassador, I'm sorry—Vartti O'Vara.
Of course, Finland is in a peculiar situation.
I remember I had my only sauna bath in his embassy.
They just can't live without those saunas, and there were two saunas, too.
We bathed after dark so that after we had our bath we could go and close our pores by rolling in the snow.
I caught pneumonia, damn near caught pneumonia.
But anyway, we met some very interesting people and never regretted it a minute, even though we didn't want the job.
Tell me about your relations with the Russians.
The Russians had a very fine staff of diplomats.
in Belgrade, because Yugoslavia was very important to them from the standpoint of controlling and diminishing the damage for no other reason.
I became very well acquainted with their senior attache, military attache.
I knew some of their diplomats, but they were hard to get to know, really.
The Communist satellite
attachés seemed to be a different breed than this Russian attaché.
He was a combat soldier.
He was a colonel.
The others all seemed to be political officers in uniform and really weren't military men, really weren't military men.
But anyway, Colonel Tarasevich and I became very good personal friends, as a matter of fact.
He and his cohorts had a
tiresome practice that they had to do under instruction.
Every time in whatever formation, whether it was a diplomatic function or an out-of-shape trip that the U.S. laws were conducting or whatever, they had to make their points of the day.
They were obligated to, I guess, by instruction.
That got a little irritating, but after we got that discussion over with- What do you mean their points of the day?
They had to discuss the merits of communism?
They had this-
For example, any significant point of difference between the U.S. and Russia of the moment, they'd state their position.

One interesting one was, you'll recall that President Kennedy shortly after he was elected met with Khrushchev in Austria and Vienna, and they had a very heated argument, you'll recall, and Khrushchev
threatened President Kennedy with what he called their rockets, their missiles, intercontinental missiles, and made a big point of this.

Well, that created quite a stir, I don't know whether you recall it or not, throughout the international community, and so that was a good example of just reinforcing with anyone who'd listen Khrushchev's position in one, his statement in one.

As a matter of fact, the Yugoslav Army was always trying to figure a way to get the attachés together about every three months and do something, either take them to Tito's battlefield or go skiing or go hunting.
They had great pheasant and grouse hunting, for example, and hare hunting in addition.
That's the kind they'd take the attachés on.
And they kind of ran out of things to do, so one time they organized a shooting match.
They had an Olympic-grade firing ranges there in Belgrade, and so they were going to have contests among the attachés firing the service rifle of Yugoslavia, the 22 rifle, and the service pistol.
So each country was competing against the other.
Well, and then we had a luncheon after the shooting to have the prizes awarded.
And it was rather embarrassing to the Yugoslav because the first three places in all three events were won by American attachés.
And I was seated by Colonel Tartasevich, the Russian attaché, and he turned to me with a glass of Slivovitza
He says, that is excellent shooting.
In Yugoslavia, of course, that is excellent shooting.
He said, I fear that we're not as good as we should be today with the small arms.
But he said, we sure are good with those rockets.
And then laughed, you know.
And I couldn't help but laugh, too.
But we became good friends.
We couldn't discuss politics, international politics, very long without getting into an argument.
But I had him in my home several times.
I never was in his.
Why not, do you think?
It would not have been right for him to.
He could accept an invitation to my home, but he could not bring me into his.
That is, to a small party.
He's had all attitudes there.
Sure.
He couldn't show any favoritism toward you.
He was a great fisherman.
He always asked me to go fishing with him.
In fact, one time when we had he and his wife and the Polish I had to share with his wife and one of my assistants and his wife for a small dinner.
After dinner, during the course of the party, Tarasiewicz asked me, when are you going to go hunting with me?
I said, well, I've got to go fishing.
I do like to fish.
He said, well, I go every Sunday, and I'm going next Sunday.
I think this was a Friday night.
And he said, I'd like for you to go with me.
I said, I'll go.
And he said, fine.
So he kind of let it drop, and as he was leaving, he said, by the way, he said, we'll leave from such and such a place, you know, to go on that fishing trip.
And he said, are you going to bring your wife?
I said, oh, no, she doesn't.
She detests fishing.
He said, well, my wife's going to insist.
She loves to fish.
And I said, oh, I can't.
My wife, I couldn't get her to go.
Why don't you and I just go alone?
And it became very clear that he couldn't go alone.
And he thought probably the most liberal course he could take would be to take his wife.
But anyway, and his wife was a nice person, sort of.
sturdy peasant type, but a very fine person.
They're children, by the way.
But you never did go fishing?
Never did go fishing, and it was my fault because the next day some, I forget who, but some senior officer came to Belgrade and I had to attend him, so I had to call it off.
And by the way, I'm not so sure about what he felt that I was getting out of it, but I don't think he did.
But, uh,
Well, were you happy to leave after living in Yugoslavia for two years?
I was ready to go.
I think Fran could have enjoyed another year because she very much enjoyed that.
She was very busy with it.
All of these official functions and social events included her.
I traveled over Yugoslavia, much of Yugoslavia, and frequently took her with me.
And there was a purpose to those travels.
And really, it was to observe.
And I and my assistants just, on a pattern, covered that whole country constantly.
And I guess I can say now- You sent back information back to Washington?
Yes.
I think I can say, you know, it was a licensed operation, you might say.
Everybody knew.
Now, we were more-
had more privilege to travel than did the Communist Bloc because they couldn't travel freely.
So they favored the Americans.
Because of our aid to them, you see.
Now we had to stay off military installations unless invited, and we had to stay off certain kilometers out of the border areas, but other than that we could travel.
Fran enjoyed that too.
She was always a little nervous about leaving the children, of course.
poor little children.
Our fourth was born there.
And Chris, our third, had been born at the War College.
But she had a good nursemaid and a good housekeeper.
And the government paid for the servants save one.
If you needed four, they'd pay for three.
And I think that was a fair way to do it.
In other words, that was to ensure that you didn't go overboard, I guess.
Sure.
Did you work with CIA people?
I may have.
But wasn't there CIA people right in the embassy?
They were not identified if they were.
So the staff was the ambassador and his State Department assistants, and then the military had a chase.
Well, we had, yes.
There was one from each?
There was one from the Air Force, Army, and Navy?
Yes.
And of course, he had a very big political department, and a very big economic department, with secretaries, first secretary in charge of each.
We worked very closely, of course, with both of them, but primarily the political.
And then you left Yugoslavia in 1961 for a very short assignment as the executive officer of the 2nd Infantry Division Artillery, and you only stayed there for four- gee whiz, for two months.
Two months, uh-huh.
And what was that, sort of a holding pattern?
No, that was another interesting thing.
Where was that?
Fort Benning, Georgia, 2nd Infantry Division Artillery.
I was the executive officer.
It was a very interesting circumstance.

I had just come back from Yugoslavia at what was considered an undesirable tour because, as I mentioned, we enjoyed it, but it was considered to be an undesirable tour, and assigned to the job I wanted.
I asked to be assigned to a division artillery.
And I thought that was a very good reward for whatever kind of a job I'd done, because they respected that wish.
But about the time I got started there, this Cuban thing, I mean, this Berlin thing came up.
Berlin Wall.
Berlin Wall and that crisis.
This added to Khrushchev's threat, had put the U.S. Army and Armed Forces into partial mobilization.
And then this division was placed in a status to be deployed if this thing went further.
And I was removed because of my recent return from overseas.
In other words, I was not deployable.
Because you just came back from overseas and because you probably didn't have enough experience to act as the executive officer in case of a crisis?
No, that had nothing to do with it.
I simply was not deployable by assignment policies.
Oh, I see.
